SYPHILIS - AUSTRALIA (02): INCREASING CASES, CONGENITAL, INDIGENOUS
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Mon 29 Oct 2018
Source: ABC (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-10-29/first-baby-born-with-syphilis-in-south-australia-in-18-years/10405846


A baby was born with congenital syphilis in Port Augusta [a small city in the state of South Australia] last year [2017], the 1st child to be born with the serious and potentially fatal disease in South Australia in 18 years.

While South Australian health authorities declared an outbreak of infectious syphilis in March last year [2017], the national response to the outbreak is still yet to be rolled out in the state.

Greens MP [Member for Parliament] Tammy Franks laid the blame for the outbreak on a lack of funding for sexual health programs. "I think all South Australians should be concerned that a child in our state is born with congenital syphilis," Ms Franks said. "That is a thing of the dark ages, it shouldn't be happening in 2018."

The Federal Government has committed AUD 8.8 million [about USD 6.25 million] to addressing the national outbreak, but Indigenous Health Minister Ken Wyatt told the ABC more funding was likely to come. "I'm certainly looking at additional funding that would assist in the process for both South Australia and other states where we are seeing an increase in syphilis outbreaks," Mr Wyatt said.

The outbreak, which is believed to have started in an Aboriginal community in northern Queensland in 2011, has spread across 4 jurisdictions to include the Northern Territory, South Australia, and Western Australia. Health Department figures show that to [30 Sep 2018 -- see [2] below], 1184 cases had been diagnosed in affected areas in Queensland, 877 in the Northern Territory, 196 in Western Australia, and 44 in South Australia.

There have been up to 15 congenital syphilis cases diagnosed in neonates or infants that are attributed to the outbreak. Of these, up to 7 babies have died.

Royal Australasian College of Physicians sexual health medicine president Catherine O'Connor said the outbreak was an "extremely serious problem that is a perfect storm. It is a totally preventable and treatable disease, it should not be happening in a wealthy country like Australia," Dr O'Connor said. "It will take years of hard work to get rates down to an acceptable level from here." She said there needed to be a long-term and sustained prevention program introduced nationally, combining sexual health education with testing.

In June [2018], a "test and treat" rapid response model was rolled out in Townsville, Cairns [Queensland], and Darwin [Northern Territory], focussing on Aboriginal people aged 15 to 29 [years]. This month [October 2018], Mr Wyatt announced testing kits would next be distributed to East Arnhem Land and Katherine in the Northern Territory, and the Kimberley region in Western Australia. But despite the passage of more than 12 months since the outbreak was announced in South Australia, the rapid response testing model is yet to be introduced in the state.

Health authorities say the remote Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara [APY] Lands, as well as the west and Eyre regions are affected. It is understood that the spread of syphilis in South Australia continues to be a major concern for regional health services, with 4 patients recently diagnosed in just one day in one clinic.

A Federal Department of Health spokeswoman said the design of the response in SA [South Australia] was still being discussed with stakeholders, including SA Health, the Aboriginal Health Council of SA and Aboriginal community controlled health services (ACCHS). "The Australian Government's contribution to the enhanced response to the syphilis outbreak is being channelled through the ACCHS sector, and that will be the case in SA," the spokeswoman said. In a statement, SA Health said it had updated the antenatal clinical guidelines to help GPs better detect syphilis before pregnancy and after birth to reduce cases of congenital syphilis.

"We're also supporting an enhanced sexually transmissible infection and blood-borne virus prevention partnership response for South Australian Aboriginal communities, which builds on the work of the Commonwealth's 'Young, Deadly, Syphilis Free campaign'," the statement said.

Aboriginal Health Council public health medical officer David Johnson said that Nganampa Health in the state's remote APY lands had a "best practice model" for sexually transmitted infection (STI) prevention that had been in place for 20 years. This program had possibly provided a buffer for South Australia from the higher rates of infection seen in other states, he said. But Dr Johnson warned numbers were rising and only 10 to 15 per cent of the Aboriginal population in other high-risk areas had been tested for syphilis.

"Some people are arguing to include Adelaide [capital city, South Australia] in the outbreak area," Dr Johnson said. "We still don't know the extent of the outbreak here."

He said Aboriginal health services were asking the Federal Government to fund additional resources to roll out the rapid response model and increase the proportion of people tested in the community.

Pregnant women with untreated early syphilis have a 70 to 100 per cent chance of passing the disease to their baby through the placenta or at birth, with up to a third of pregnancies resulting in miscarriage or stillbirth. Infected babies who aren't treated can have seizures, brain damage, blindness, developmental delay, or die.

The rapid response test functions similarly to the blood sugar test many diabetics do regularly -- it is a pin prick blood test that delivers a quick result. Traditionally, tests for syphilis take up to two weeks to process for results.

[Byline: Rebecca Puddy]

