[ProMED-mail has previously reported the ongoing syphilis outbreak among young heterosexual indigenous people in remote communities that has spread across Australia since 2011 and that has been associated with increasing numbers of cases of congenital syphilis (Syphilis - Australia (02): (NT,WA) increase, indigenous, congenital, fatal 20151102.3760394, Syphilis - Australia: (NT) increased incidence, indigenous people, RFI 20150713.3507530, and Syphilis - Australia (03): (QL) indigenous, RFI 20120808.1234631).

Aboriginal and Torres Straight Islander people (Indigenous Australians) includes many regional groups. There are about 650 000 Indigenous Australians; they make up about 25 per cent of the population in the Northern Territory, 4.0 per cent of the population in Queensland, 3.0 per cent of the population in Western Australia, 3 percent in New South Wales, 2.0 per cent in South Australia, 4.6 percent in Tasmania, and less than 1 per cent in the Capital Territory (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_Australians).

70 per cent of the indigenous population live outside major cities, of which about 1/3 live in remote communities, where access to health services is likely to be poor (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_Australians): "Only 20 per cent of Aboriginal people who live in remote communities of more than 50 people have access to a doctor on a daily basis according to Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) figures from 2006. A further 41 per cent have local access to a doctor once a week or once a fortnight" (http://www.creativespirits.info/aboriginalculture/health/hospitals-doctors-health-aboriginal-people#ixzz3fk6Jag2m).

The reports above say that Anangu Pitjantjatjara Yankunytjatjara (APY) (included in the Far North Government Region), as well as the Eyre and Western Region are the affected areas in South Australia. APY is a large Aboriginal local government area located in the remote northwestern corner of South Australia and the Eyre and Western Region is the Eyre Peninsula, a triangular peninsula, and the coastline extending west to South Australia's border with Western Australia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eyre_Peninsula).

APY has a population of around 2500 residents, about 85 percent of whom are Indigenous Australians (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anangu_Pitjantjatjara_Yankunytjatjara). The Eyre and Western Region has a population of almost 60 thousand residents, only 4.4 percent of whom are estimated to be Indigenous (https: //en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eyre_Peninsula). Indigenous Australians are located in 3 communities in Eyre and Western region: Maralinga Tjarutja Lands in the far west, Yalata 350 km [about 217.5 mi] to the south and Koonibba a further 188 km [about 117 mi] to the southeast (https://www.sa.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0018/7290/Eyre_and_Western_Region_Plan.pdf). For a map showing the location of APY, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anangu_Pitjantjatjara_Yankunytjatjara, and for a map of South Australia showing the Eyre and Western Region, see https://www.researchgate.net/profile/John_Spoehr/publication/236165460/figure/fig3/AS:299436707205122@1448402682202/South-Australian-Government-regions.png).

Maps of Australia can be seen at http://maps.unomaha.edu/peterson/funda/MapLinks/Australia/Australia_files/image001.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6119580,186. - Mod.ML]
